# 3) Coefficients and variance-covariances

It's important to keep in mind when working with models that the goal is not only to obtain an estimate but also to express the uncertainity around that estimation. To show that let's focus on the complete model and remember that 

$$ \boldsymbol{\hat\beta} = (\boldsymbol{X^\top X})^{-1} \boldsymbol{X^\top} \boldsymbol{y} $$
$$V(\boldsymbol{\hat{\beta}}) = (\boldsymbol{X^\top X})^{-1} \sigma^2$$

So, to compute the variance of the estimation we first need to estimate 
$\sigma^2$. We will see in following chapters the complexity of doing so, but for now, 
it can be inferred from the Sum of Square Errors



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
sigma_2 <- SSE / (n - length(beta))
vcov_betas <- XtX_inv * sigma_2
vcov_betas
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

